T1	Participants 1187 1316	CONCLUSIONS Findings suggest that teachers were able to improve a core deficit of children with ASD in a public preschool context
T2	Participants 115 252	OBJECTIVE The vast majority of children with an autism spectrum disorder (ASD) attend public preschools at some point in their childhood.
T3	Participants 820 1024	RESULTS At the end of the intervention, JASP/ER teachers used more JASP/ER strategies than the control teachers, and JASP/ER preschoolers used more joint attention in their classroom than control children
T4	Participants 630 818	METHOD Sixteen dyads (preschoolers with ASD and the public school teachers who worked in the child's classroom) were randomly assigned to the 6-week JASP/ER intervention or a control group
